Type aliasses are not deprecated, neither are interfaces, they both have their uses.

For simple scenarios there is little difference between the two. You can use them mostly interchangeably. 

Type aliases supports several advanced types such as [mapped types](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/advanced-types.html#mapped-types) and [conditional types](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/advanced-types.html#conditional-types). 

Interfaces support some recursive scenarios better, although type aliases also allow recursion in certain scenarios, and the gap between what recursiveness is allowed in interface and type aliases is closing (see [PR](https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/pull/33050)).

 Interfaces also support [merging](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/declaration-merging.html#merging-interfaces) with classes and functions and other redeclarations of the same interface. Ex:

```ts
interface Box {
    height: number;
    width: number;
}

interface Box {
    scale: number;
}

let box: Box = {height: 5, width: 6, scale: 10};
```

Also worth mentioning is that object types from interfaces are not assignable to a type with an index signature, while an object type from a type alias is. 

```ts
function fn(a: { [s:string]: string}){}

interface I { a: string}
type T = { a: string }

declare let i:I;
declare let t:T;

fn(i) //err
fn(t)

```
[Play](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play/index.html#code/GYVwdgxgLglg9mABMMAKAhgLkQb0QbQGdNCoAnGMAcwF1tSLqBfAShyYCgPKoBTM4Ogi9EASVyIsiBpSqcoATwAOIgCqIAvBKkzqiThwAmvCABt0ZEad5REMTKIDcRk+cuJrtqJlXOOKVBgWfzQoYKA)

